-- Sugar Money Managers’ Bets on Price Rise Soar, Liffe Says
-- B y   I s i s   A l m e i d a
-- 2012-01-30T13:45:07Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2012-01-30/sugar-money-managers-bets-on-price-rise-soar-liffe-says-1-.html
Money managers’ bets on rising white
sugar prices soared in the week ended Jan. 24, according to
figures from NYSE Liffe, the derivatives arm of NYSE Euronext.  Net-long positions, or bets on higher prices, climbed to
3,286 contracts, according to the weekly commitments of traders
report published on the exchange’s  website  today. That compares
with a net-long position of 559 futures on Jan. 17, exchange
data show. Net long positions increased for a fourth week.  White sugar climbed 4.6 percent in London in the period on
speculation supplies would be limited in the first quarter.
Global sugar supplies may be limited for the next two months on
speculation the U.S. will need to import from countries in
Central America because of falling output from traditional
supplier  Mexico , Bruno Zaneti, a consultant at FCStone do Brasil
in Campinas,  Brazil , said on Jan. 18.  In robusta coffee, money managers trimmed their net-short
position by 24 percent to 8,238 contracts, according to the
data. Robusta coffee rose 2.3 percent in the period.  Cocoa money managers increased their net-long positions by
24 percent to 6,471 contracts, the exchange data show. Cocoa
jumped 5.3 percent in the period. Net-long positions climbed for
a third consecutive week.  In feed wheat, money managers were net-short of 330
contracts, up from 321 contracts a week earlier, the data show.
Feed wheat rose 4 percent in the period.  To contact the reporter on this story:
